        "assistant": "An **elastic automator** and an **AI agent** are different mainly in *how they make decisions* and *what they’re designed to do*.\n\n### Elastic automator\nAn **elastic automator** is usually a rule-based or workflow-based automation system that can scale or adjust based on changing conditions.\n\nFor example:\n\n- If website traffic increases, add more servers.\n- If CPU usage drops, remove unused servers.\n- If an Elasticsearch index gets too large, create a new one.\n- If a scheduled job fails, restart it.\n\nIt is usually based on predefined rules, triggers, scripts, or policies.\n\n### AI agent\nAn **AI agent** is a system that can use AI to reason, plan, make decisions, and take actions toward a goal.\n\nFor example:\n\n- “Investigate why our search service is slow.”\n- It checks logs, looks at metrics, identifies a likely cause, and suggests or performs a fix.\n- It may decide which tools to use and adjust its plan as it learns more.\n\nAn AI agent is usually more flexible and goal-driven.\n\n### Simple difference\n\n| Feature | Elastic automator | AI agent |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main purpose | Automate and scale tasks | Reason and act toward goals |\n| Decision-making | Mostly rules or workflows | AI-based reasoning and planning |\n| Flexibility | Limited to predefined conditions | More adaptive and context-aware |\n| Example | “If CPU > 80%, add server” | “Find out why the app is slow and fix it” |\n| Common use | Cloud scaling, DevOps automation, Elastic Stack tasks | Support bots, coding agents, research agents, operations agents |\n\n### In short\n\nAn **elastic automator** usually follows predefined automation rules and adjusts resources or tasks dynamically.\n\nAn **AI agent** can interpret goals, make decisions, use tools, and adapt its behavior more intelligently.\n\nSo an elastic automator might answer:  \n> “CPU is high, so I will add another server.”\n\nAn AI agent might answer:  \n> “CPU is high because a bad database query is 