        "assistant": "An **elastic automator** differs from an **RPA bot** mainly in *where it operates*, *how it scales*, and *what kind of automation it performs*.\n\n### RPA bot\n\nAn **RPA bot** — Robotic Process Automation bot — automates repetitive human tasks, usually through user interfaces.\n\nExamples:\n\n- Copying data from an email into a spreadsheet\n- Logging into a website and downloading invoices\n- Moving data between legacy business systems\n- Filling out forms\n- Processing claims or purchase orders\n\nRPA bots often imitate what a human user would do on a computer.\n\n### Elastic automator\n\nAn **elastic automator** is more likely an automation system that adapts dynamically to workload or system conditions.\n\nExamples:\n\n- Adding more cloud servers when traffic increases\n- Reducing resources when demand drops\n- Automatically managing Elasticsearch indexes\n- Restarting failed services\n- Scaling data pipelines based on queue size\n- Adjusting infrastructure based on metrics\n\nIt is usually more infrastructure-, system-, or workload-focused.\n\n### Simple comparison\n\n| Feature | Elastic automator | RPA bot |\n|---|---|---|\n| Main focus | Dynamic automation and scaling | Repetitive business/process tasks |\n| Typical environment | Cloud, DevOps, infrastructure, data systems | Desktop apps, web apps, enterprise systems |\n| How it acts | Uses APIs, scripts, policies, metrics, workflows | Mimics human clicks, typing, copying, form filling |\n| Scaling behavior | Designed to expand/shrink with demand | Usually runs fixed task workflows |\n| Example | “If traffic spikes, add more servers” | “Open invoice email, extract amount, enter it into ERP” |\n| Flexibility | Adapts to system conditions | Follows predefined process steps |\n\n### In short\n\nAn **RPA bot** automates what a human office worker might do manually.\n\nAn **elastic automator** automates system behavior that changes based on demand, workload, or operational conditions.\n\nSo:\